ReportesCobranza&&
ReportesCobranza&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
ReportesCobranza&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
ReportesCobranza&&accessIds:
ReportesCobranza&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
ReportesCobranza&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
ReportesCobranza&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
ReportesCobranza&&AllAuthenticated:
ReportesCobranza&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
ReportesCobranza&&Role:  MXApp_FV_AGENTEING
ReportesCobranza&&Everyone?:  No
ReportesCobranza&&All authenticated?:  No
ReportesCobranza&&Mapped users:

ReportesCobranza&&
ReportesCobranza&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
ReportesCobranza&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.

SIEScssApplication&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
SIEScssApplication&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

SIESdspeiApplicationA&&
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&Module:  SIESdspeiApplication-ejb.jar
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&Bean:  SessionBean
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&URI:  SIESdspeiApplication-ejb.jar,META-INF/ejb-jar.xml
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&Target Resource JNDI Name:  null
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&Local Home JNDI Name:  null
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&Remote Home JNDI Name:  null
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&BindJndiForEJBBusiness: Binding enterprise Bean with business interface to JNDI names
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&Each enterprise bean with a business interface in a module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For any business interface that does not provide a JNDI name, 
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&if its bean does not provide a JNDI name, a default binding name is provided.
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&If its bean provides a JNDI name, then a default is provided on top of its bean JNDI name.
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&Module:  SIESdspeiApplication-ejb.jar
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&Bean:  SessionBean
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&URI:  SIESdspeiApplication-ejb.jar,META-INF/ejb-jar.xml
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&Business interface:  com.sies.aplic.pagoselectronicos.servlet.SessionBeanLocal

SIESdspeiApplicationA&&URI:  SIESdspeiApplication-ejb.jar,META-INF/ejb-jar.xml

SIESdspeiApplicationA&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
SIESdspeiApplicationA&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

SMSWeb_war&&Use JASPI:  Inherit
SMSWeb_war&&JASPI provider name:  
SMSWeb_war&&
SMSWeb_war&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
SMSWeb_war&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
SMSWeb_war&&accessIds:
SMSWeb_war&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
SMSWeb_war&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
SMSWeb_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
SMSWeb_war&&AllAuthenticated:
SMSWeb_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
SMSWeb_war&&Role:  Alertas_ADMIN
SMSWeb_war&&Everyone?:  No
SMSWeb_war&&All authenticated?:  No
SMSWeb_war&&Mapped users:  
SMSWeb_war&&Mapped groups:  MXApps_Alertas_ADMIN

SMSWeb_war&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
SMSWeb_war&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance. 
SMSWeb_war&&Module:  Portal de Alertas
SMSWeb_war&&URI:  SMSWeb.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
SMSWeb_war&&metadata-complete attribute:  false

SSO&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
SSO&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.

SSO&&Bean:  AccessManager

SSO2&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
SSO2&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.

SaludWeb&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
SaludWeb&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
SaludWeb&&accessIds:
SaludWeb&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
SaludWeb&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
SaludWeb&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
SaludWeb&&AllAuthenticated:
SaludWeb&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
SaludWeb&&Role:  RECEPTOR
SaludWeb&&Everyone?:  No
SaludWeb&&All authenticated?:  No
SaludWeb&&Mapped users:  
SaludWeb&&Mapped groups:  MXAppS_SGMyS_Receptor

SaludWeb2&&MapJaspiProvider: Configure JASPI authentication.
SaludWeb2&&JASPI providers offer an alternative to JAAS pluggable authentication for web modules.  By default, an application inherits the JASPI settings defined in the WebSphere Application Server global or domain security configuration and web modules inherit the application setting.  However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.

SaludWeb2&&
SaludWeb2&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
SaludWeb2&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
SaludWeb2&&accessIds:
SaludWeb2&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
SaludWeb2&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
SaludWeb2&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
SaludWeb2&&AllAuthenticated:
SaludWeb2&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

SaludWebPP&&MapModulesToServers: Selecting servers
SaludWebPP&&Specify targets such as application servers or clusters of application servers where you want to install the modules that are contained in your application. Modules can be installed on the same application server or dispersed among several application servers. 
SaludWebPP&&Also, specify the Web servers as targets that serve as routers for requests to this application. 
SaludWebPP&&The plug-in configuration file (plugin-cfg.xml) for each Web server is generated, based on the applications that are routed through.

SaludWebPP&&MapJaspiProvider: Configure JASPI authentication.
SaludWebPP&&JASPI providers offer an alternative to JAAS pluggable authentication for web modules.  By default, an application inherits the JASPI settings defined in the WebSphere Application Server global or domain security configuration and web modules inherit the application setting.  However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.

SaludWebPP&&
SaludWebPP&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
SaludWebPP&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
SaludWebPP&&accessIds:
SaludWebPP&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
SaludWebPP&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
SaludWebPP&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
SaludWebPP&&AllAuthenticated:
SaludWebPP&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

SaludWebWS&&MapJaspiProvider: Configure JASPI authentication.
SaludWebWS&&JASPI providers offer an alternative to JAAS pluggable authentication for web modules.  By default, an application inherits the JASPI settings defined in the WebSphere Application Server global or domain security configuration and web modules inherit the application setting.  However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.

SaludWebWS&&URI:  META-INF/application.xml
SaludWebWS&&Use JASPI:  Inherit

SaludWebWS&&
SaludWebWS&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
SaludWebWS&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
SaludWebWS&&accessIds:
SaludWebWS&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
SaludWebWS&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
SaludWebWS&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
SaludWebWS&&AllAuthenticated:
SaludWebWS&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

SaludWebWSPP&&Also, specify the Web servers as targets that serve as routers for requests to this application. 
SaludWebWSPP&&The plug-in configuration file (plugin-cfg.xml) for each Web server is generated, based on the applications that are routed through.
SaludWebWSPP&&Module:  SaludWebWS
SaludWebWSPP&&URI:  SaludWebWS.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
SaludWebWSPP&&Server:  WebSphere:cell=AXACellQA,cluster=cluster03_PreProd+WebSphere:cell=AXACellQA,node=apacheNode01QA,server=apacheExt_QA1+WebSphere:cell=AXACellQA,node=apacheNode02QA,server=apacheExt_QA2
SaludWebWSPP&&
SaludWebWSPP&&MapJaspiProvider: Configure JASPI authentication.
SaludWebWSPP&&JASPI providers offer an alternative to JAAS pluggable authentication for web modules.  By default, an application inherits the JASPI settings defined in the WebSphere Application Server global or domain security configuration and web modules inherit the application setting.  However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.
SaludWebWSPP&&Module:  SaludWebWSPP
SaludWebWSPP&&URI:  META-INF/application.xml
SaludWebWSPP&&Use JASPI:  Inherit
SaludWebWSPP&&JASPI provider name:  
SaludWebWSPP&&Module:  SaludWebWS
SaludWebWSPP&&URI:  SaludWebWS.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
SaludWebWSPP&&Use JASPI:  Inherit
SaludWebWSPP&&JASPI provider name:  
SaludWebWSPP&&
SaludWebWSPP&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
SaludWebWSPP&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
SaludWebWSPP&&accessIds:
SaludWebWSPP&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
SaludWebWSPP&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
SaludWebWSPP&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
SaludWebWSPP&&AllAuthenticated:
SaludWebWSPP&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
SaludWebWSPP&&Role:  MXAppS_SGMyS_WS
SaludWebWSPP&&Everyone?:  No
SaludWebWSPP&&All authenticated?:  No
SaludWebWSPP&&Mapped users:  
SaludWebWSPP&&Mapped groups:  MXAppS_SGMyS_WS
SaludWebWSPP&&All authenticated in trusted realms?:  No
SaludWebWSPP&&Mapped users access ids:  
SaludWebWSPP&&Mapped groups access ids:  group:AXARealm/CN=MXAppS_SGMyS_WS,OU=Groups,OU=Usuarios,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX

ServiciosComunesWS&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
ServiciosComunesWS&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
ServiciosComunesWS&&accessIds:
ServiciosComunesWS&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
ServiciosComunesWS&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
ServiciosComunesWS&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
ServiciosComunesWS&&AllAuthenticated:
ServiciosComunesWS&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

By default, an application inherits the JASPI settings defined in the WebSphere Application Server global or domain security configuration and web modules inherit the application setting.  However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.

TipoDeCambio_war&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
TipoDeCambio_war&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
TipoDeCambio_war&&accessIds:
TipoDeCambio_war&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
TipoDeCambio_war&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
TipoDeCambio_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
TipoDeCambio_war&&AllAuthenticated:
TipoDeCambio_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
TipoDeCambio_war&&Role:  MXApps_TipoCambio_Administrador
TipoDeCambio_war&&Everyone?:  No
TipoDeCambio_war&&All authenticated?:  No
TipoDeCambio_war&&Mapped users:  
TipoDeCambio_war&&Mapped groups:  MXApps_TipoCambio_Administrador

UtilsMiddleware&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
UtilsMiddleware&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. ValidarCedulasWS&&accessIds:
ValidarCedulasWS&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.

ValuacionMovilWSpreprod&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

VisorCFDPlusXApp_war&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
VisorCFDPlusXApp_war&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

WSDanosPymes&&MapJaspiProvider: Configure JASPI authentication.
WSDanosPymes&&JASPI providers offer an alternative to JAAS pluggable authentication for web modules.  By default, an application inherits the JASPI settings defined in the WebSphere Application Server global or domain security configuration and web modules inherit the application setting.  However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.

WSDanosPymes&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
WSDanosPymes&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
WSDanosPymes&&accessIds:
WSDanosPymes&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
WSDanosPymes&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
WSDanosPymes&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
WSDanosPymes&&AllAuthenticated:
WSDanosPymes&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

WSDanosPymes&&All authenticated?:  No
WSDanosPymes&&Mapped users:

WebServiceClient_war&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
WebServiceClient_war&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

WorkSite&&
WorkSite&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
WorkSite&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
WorkSite&&accessIds:
WorkSite&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
WorkSite&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
WorkSite&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
WorkSite&&AllAuthenticated:
WorkSite&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
WorkSite&&Role:  AdministratorWorkSite
WorkSite&&Everyone?:  No
WorkSite&&All authenticated?:  No
WorkSite&&Mapped users:  
WorkSite&&Mapped groups:  MXAppS_EMA_WkSt_Administrador
WorkSite&&All authenticated in trusted realms?:  No
WorkSite&&Mapped users access ids:  
WorkSite&&Mapped groups access ids:  group:AXARealm/CN=MXAppS_EMA_WkSt_Administrador,OU=Groups,OU=Usuarios,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX
WorkSite&&Role:  ImplantWorkSite
WorkSite&&Everyone?:  No
WorkSite&&All authenticated?:  No
WorkSite&&Mapped users:  
WorkSite&&Mapped groups:  MXAppS_EMA_WkSt_Implant
WorkSite&&All authenticated in trusted realms?:  No
WorkSite&&Mapped users access ids:

XDCGIVT&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
XDCGIVT&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.
XDCGIVT&&Module:  XDCGIVTEJBs
XDCGIVT&&Bean:  XDCGIVTBatchController
XDCGIVT&&URI:  XDCGIVTEJBs.jar,META-INF/ejb-jar.xml

adminContacting&&MapModulesToServers: Selecting servers
adminContacting&&Specify targets such as application servers or clusters of application servers where you want to install the modules that are contained in your application. Modules can be installed on the same application server or dispersed among several application servers.

adminContacting&&MapJaspiProvider: Configure JASPI authentication.
adminContacting&&JASPI providers offer an alternative to JAAS pluggable authentication for web modules.  By default, an application inherits the JASPI settings defined in the WebSphere Application Server global or domain security configuration and web modules inherit the application setting.  However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.

adminContacting&&JASPI provider name:  
adminContacting&&
adminContacting&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
adminContacting&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
adminContacting&&accessIds:
adminContacting&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
adminContacting&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
adminContacting&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
adminContacting&&AllAuthenticated:
adminContacting&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
adminContacting&&Role:  MXApp_FV_CONTACTING_ADM
adminContacting&&Everyone?:  No
adminContacting&&All authenticated?:  No
adminContacting&&Mapped users:  MXE01502931A
adminContacting&&Mapped groups:  MXApp_FV_CONTACTING_ADM
adminContacting&&All authenticated in trusted realms?:  No
adminContacting&&Mapped users access ids:  user:AXARealm/CN=DE LA PEA VASCONCELOS VICTOR ENRIQUE,OU=Usuarios Externos,OU=Usuarios,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX

axaEmisionSalud&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

bci-ear&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
bci-ear&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

bonos&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
bonos&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
bonos&&accessIds:
bonos&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
bonos&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
bonos&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
bonos&&AllAuthenticated:
bonos&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

bonos&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
bonos&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.

bumerang-ear&&MapModulesToServers: Selecting servers
bumerang-ear&&Specify targets such as application servers or clusters of application servers where you want to install the modules that are contained in your application. Modules can be installed on the same application server or dispersed among several application servers. 
bumerang-ear&&Also, specify the Web servers as targets that serve as routers for requests to this application. 
bumerang-ear&&The plug-in configuration file (plugin-cfg.xml) for each Web server is generated, based on the applications that are routed through.
bumerang-ear&&Module:  bumerang-web-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war

bumerang-ear&&MapJaspiProvider: Configure JASPI authentication.
bumerang-ear&&JASPI providers offer an alternative to JAAS pluggable authentication for web modules.  By default, an application inherits the JASPI settings defined in the WebSphere Application Server global or domain security configuration and web modules inherit the application setting.  However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.

bumerang-ear&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
bumerang-ear&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
bumerang-ear&&accessIds:
bumerang-ear&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
bumerang-ear&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
bumerang-ear&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
bumerang-ear&&AllAuthenticated:
bumerang-ear&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

catComServ&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
catComServ&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.

contacting&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
contacting&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
contacting&&accessIds:
contacting&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.

contacting&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
contacting&&AllAuthenticated:
contacting&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

contacting&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.

cotizadores_war&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
cotizadores_war&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
cotizadores_war&&accessIds:
cotizadores_war&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
cotizadores_war&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
cotizadores_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
cotizadores_war&&AllAuthenticated:
cotizadores_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
cotizadores_war&&Role:  wksAdmin
cotizadores_war&&Everyone?:  No
cotizadores_war&&All authenticated?:  No
cotizadores_war&&Mapped users:  
cotizadores_war&&Mapped groups:  MXAppS_PVM_AdminPVMWorksite|MXAppS_PVM_AdminPVMTI|MXAppS_PVM_AdminPVM
cotizadores_war&&All authenticated in trusted realms?:  No
cotizadores_war&&Mapped users access ids:  
cotizadores_war&&Mapped groups access ids:  group:AXARealm/CN=MXAppS_PVM_AdminPVMWorksite,OU=Groups,OU=Usuarios,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX|group:AXARealm/CN=MXAppS_PVM_AdminPVMTI,OU=Groups,OU=Usuarios,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX|group:AXARealm/CN=MXAppS_PVM_AdminPVM,OU=Groups,OU=Usuarios,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX

endososSalud_war&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
endososSalud_war&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

facturaElectronica_war&&
facturaElectronica_war&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
facturaElectronica_war&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
facturaElectronica_war&&accessIds:
facturaElectronica_war&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
facturaElectronica_war&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
facturaElectronica_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
facturaElectronica_war&&AllAuthenticated:
facturaElectronica_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

gmmiweb&&
gmmiweb&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
gmmiweb&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.
gmmiweb&&Module:  inggmmiEAR
gmmiweb&&Bean:  GMM_com_ing_mx_ia3_seguros_gmm_TipoCambioMensualHome
gmmiweb&&URI:  inggmmiEJB.jar,META-INF/ejb-jar.xml
gmmiweb&&Target Resource JNDI Name:  GMM_com_ing_mx_ia3_seguros_gmm_TipoCambioMensualHome

gmmiweb_2&&JASPI providers offer an alternative to JAAS pluggable authentication for web modules. However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.

gmmiweb_2&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
gmmiweb_2&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
gmmiweb_2&&accessIds:
gmmiweb_2&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
gmmiweb_2&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
gmmiweb_2&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
gmmiweb_2&&AllAuthenticated:
gmmiweb_2&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

gmmiweb_2&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
gmmiweb_2&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
gmmiweb_2&&accessIds:
gmmiweb_2&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
gmmiweb_2&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
gmmiweb_2&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
gmmiweb_2&&AllAuthenticated:
gmmiweb_2&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

gmmiweb_2&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
gmmiweb_2&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.

However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.

iwcfdAxaWeb&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles

iwcfdAxaWeb&&accessIds:
iwcfdAxaWeb&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
iwcfdAxaWeb&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
iwcfdAxaWeb&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
iwcfdAxaWeb&&AllAuthenticated:
iwcfdAxaWeb&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

iwcfdAxaWeb&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
iwcfdAxaWeb&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

iwcfdWeb&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
iwcfdWeb&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.

iwcfdWeb&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
iwcfdWeb&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.

liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&accessIds:
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&AllAuthenticated:
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&Role:  users
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&Everyone?:  No
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&All authenticated?:  No
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&Mapped users:  
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&Mapped groups:  
liferay-portal-6_2-ee-sp20-20170717160924965_war&&All authenticated in trusted realms?:  No

mds&&MapModulesToServers: Selecting servers
mds&&Specify targets such as application servers or clusters of application servers where you want to install the modules that are contained in your application. Modules can be installed on the same application server or dispersed among several application servers. 
mds&&Also, specify the Web servers as targets that serve as routers for requests to this application. 
mds&&The plug-in configuration file (plugin-cfg.xml) for each Web server is generated, based on the applications that are routed through.
mds&&Module:  MDS
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&Server:  WebSphere:cell=AXACellQA,node=apacheNode02QA,server=apacheExt_QA2+WebSphere:cell=AXACellQA,node=apacheNode01QA,server=apacheExt_QA1+WebSphere:cell=AXACellQA,cluster=cluster17_QA
mds&&
mds&&MapJaspiProvider: Configure JASPI authentication.
mds&&JASPI providers offer an alternative to JAAS pluggable authentication for web modules.  By default, an application inherits the JASPI settings defined in the WebSphere Application Server global or domain security configuration and web modules inherit the application setting.  However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.
mds&&Module:  mds
mds&&URI:  META-INF/application.xml
mds&&Use JASPI:  Inherit
mds&&JASPI provider name:  
mds&&Module:  MDS
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&Use JASPI:  Inherit
mds&&JASPI provider name:  
mds&&
mds&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
mds&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
mds&&accessIds:
mds&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
mds&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
mds&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
mds&&AllAuthenticated:
mds&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
mds&&Role:  SecRole
mds&&Everyone?:  No
mds&&All authenticated?:  No
mds&&Mapped users:  MXS00100163A
mds&&Mapped groups:  SecRole|MXAppS_MDSservice_WS
mds&&All authenticated in trusted realms?:  No
mds&&Mapped users access ids:  user:AXARealm/CN=Yiselle Troncoso Shallivad (Web Services Alertas Naranja),OU=Usuarios de Servicio,OU=Usuarios,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX
mds&&Mapped groups access ids:  group:AXARealm/CN=SecRole,OU=Groups,OU=Usuarios,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX|group:AXARealm/CN=MXAppS_MDSservice_WS,OU=Groups,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX
mds&&
mds&&MapResRefToEJB: Mapping resource references to resources
mds&&Each resource reference that is defined in your application must be mapped to a resource.
mds&&Module:  MDS
mds&&Bean:  
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&Resource Reference:  jdbc/MDS
mds&&Resource type:  javax.sql.DataSource
mds&&Target Resource JNDI Name:  jdbc/MDS
mds&&Login configuration name:  
mds&&Properties:  
mds&&Extended Data source properties:  
mds&&Module:  MDS
mds&&Bean:  
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&Resource Reference:  contactINGDS
mds&&Resource type:  javax.sql.DataSource
mds&&Target Resource JNDI Name:  contactINGDS
mds&&Login configuration name:  
mds&&Properties:  
mds&&Extended Data source properties:  
mds&&
mds&&MapWebModToVH: Selecting virtual hosts for Web modules
mds&&Specify the virtual host for the Web modules that are contained in your application. You can install Web modules on the same virtual host or disperse them among several hosts.
mds&&Web module:  MDS
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&Virtual host:  default_ext
mds&&

mds&&Configure values for context roots in web modules.
mds&&Web module:  MDS
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&Context Root:  /mds
mds&&

mds&&
mds&&MapSharedLibForMod: Assign shared libraries to application or each module
mds&&Specify shared libraries that the application or individual modules reference. These libraries must be defined in the configuration at the appropriate scope.
mds&&Module:  MDS
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&Shared Libraries:  
mds&&
mds&&SharedLibRelationship: Assign asset or composition unit IDs as shared libraries to the application or each module
mds&&Specify asset or composition unit IDs as shared libraries that the application or individual modules reference. If a composition unit ID is specified, it must be part of the business level application that this enterprise application belongs to. If an asset ID is specified, a composition unit is created from the asset.
mds&&When editing an application, only composition unit IDs can be specified as shared libraries.
mds&&Module:  MDS
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&Asset or composition unit IDs:  
mds&&Composition Unit names:  
mds&&Match target:  Yes
mds&&
mds&&JSPReloadForWebMod: Specify JSP reload options for web module
mds&&Configure Servlet and JSP reload attributes in web modules.
mds&&Web module:  MDS
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&JSP enable class reloading:  Yes
mds&&JSP reload interval in seconds:  10
mds&&
mds&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
mds&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance. 
mds&&Module:  MDS
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&metadata-complete attribute:  false
mds&&
mds&&CustomActivationPlan: Specify runtime provisioning components to be added or removed
mds&&Specify runtime components that should be added to or removed from the default runtime components that are needed to run this application.  This step is for advanced users and should only be used in those cases when all the runtime components needed for the application cannot be obtained by inspecting the application.
mds&&Module:  MDS
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&Runtime Provisioning Components To Add:  
mds&&Runtime Provisioning Components To Remove:  
mds&&
mds&&ModuleBuildID: Module Build ID
mds&&Display module build IDs.
mds&&Module:  MDS
mds&&URI:  mds.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
mds&&Build ID:

rcuweb&&
rcuweb&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
rcuweb&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
rcuweb&&accessIds:
rcuweb&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
rcuweb&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
rcuweb&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
rcuweb&&AllAuthenticated:
rcuweb&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
rcuweb&&Role:  consulta
rcuweb&&Everyone?:  No
rcuweb&&All authenticated?:  No
rcuweb&&Mapped users:  
rcuweb&&Mapped groups:  MXAppINT_RCU_Consulta
rcuweb&&All authenticated in trusted realms?:  No
rcuweb&&Mapped users access ids:  
rcuweb&&Mapped groups access ids:  group:AXARealm/CN=MXAppINT_RCU_Consulta,OU=Groups,OU=Usuarios,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX

However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.

rcuweb&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
rcuweb&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
rcuweb&&accessIds:
rcuweb&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
rcuweb&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
rcuweb&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
rcuweb&&AllAuthenticated:
rcuweb&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.

reservasSiniestrosLitigio&&BindJndiForEJBNonMessageBinding: Binding enterprise Bean to JNDI names
reservasSiniestrosLitigio&&Each non-message-driven enterprise bean in your application or module must be bound to a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name. For beans in a pre-EJB 3.0 module, you have to use JNDI name for the bean to provide the binding. For beans in a EJB 3.0 module, you can optionally provide binding through JNDI name for the bean or local/remote home JNDI names. If JNDI name for the bean is specified, you cannot specify binding for its local/remote home and any business interface. If no JNDI name is specified for beans in a EJB 3.0 module, runtime will provide a container default.

solvency_war&&MapModulesToServers: Selecting servers
solvency_war&&Specify targets such as application servers or clusters of application servers where you want to install the modules that are contained in your application. Modules can be installed on the same application server or dispersed among several application servers. 
solvency_war&&Also, specify the Web servers as targets that serve as routers for requests to this application. 
solvency_war&&The plug-in configuration file (plugin-cfg.xml) for each Web server is generated, based on the applications that are routed through.

solvency_war&&Server:  WebSphere:cell=AXACellQA,cluster=cluster22_QA+WebSphere:cell=AXACellQA,node=apacheNode01QA,server=apacheInt_QA1+WebSphere:cell=AXACellQA,node=apacheNode02QA,server=apacheInt_QA2
solvency_war&&
solvency_war&&MapJaspiProvider: Configure JASPI authentication.
solvency_war&&JASPI providers offer an alternative to JAAS pluggable authentication for web modules.  By default, an application inherits the JASPI settings defined in the WebSphere Application Server global or domain security configuration and web modules inherit the application setting.  However, you can override these defaults by using wsadmin or the administrative console.
solvency_war&&Module:  solvency_war
solvency_war&&URI:  META-INF/application.xml
solvency_war&&Use JASPI:  Inherit
solvency_war&&JASPI provider name:  
solvency_war&&Module:  Solvency
solvency_war&&URI:  solvency.war,WEB-INF/web.xml
solvency_war&&Use JASPI:  Inherit
solvency_war&&JASPI provider name:  
solvency_war&&
solvency_war&&MapRolesToUsers: Mapping users to roles
solvency_war&&Each role that is defined in the application or module must map to a user or group from the domain user registry.
solvency_war&&accessIds:
solvency_war&&	The accessIds are required only when using cross realm communication in a multi domain scenario. For all other scenarios the accessId will be determined during the application start based on the user or group name. The accessIds represent the user and group information that is used for Java Platform, Enterprise Edition authorization when using the WebSphere default authorization engine. The format for the accessIds is user:realm/uniqueUserID, group:realm/uniqueGroupID. Entering wrong information in these fields will cause authorization to fail.
solvency_war&&AllAuthenticatedInTrustedRealms:
solvency_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the trusted realms be given the access.
solvency_war&&AllAuthenticated:
solvency_war&&	This indicates that any valid user in the current realm be given the access.
solvency_war&&Role:  SolvencyUserInfoRole
solvency_war&&Everyone?:  No
solvency_war&&All authenticated?:  No
solvency_war&&Mapped users:  
solvency_war&&Mapped groups:  MXAppS_Solvency
solvency_war&&All authenticated in trusted realms?:  No
solvency_war&&Mapped users access ids:  
solvency_war&&Mapped groups access ids:  group:AXARealm/CN=MXAppS_Solvency,OU=Groups,OU=Usuarios,OU=AXA Mexico,DC=ASEFITEST,DC=MEX
solvency_war&&

solvency_war&&MetadataCompleteForModules: Set the metadata-complete attribute of the deployment descriptor for the module
solvency_war&&The metadata-complete attribute defines whether the deployment descriptor for this module is complete. Set the metadata-complete attribute to "true" to merge and persist annotation-based metadata with existing XML-based deployment descriptor metedata to avoid scanning of annotation-based metadata each time the module is read. If the attribute remains "false", then the annotation-based metadata is scanned each time the module is read and can impact performance.
